This was our worst experience eating outside in a restaurant post pandemic and Hing Kee made it possible. First of all, the attitude of the people managing and serving in Hing Kee is awful. They put up a ‘Don’t care attitude for customers’. They served us with utter apathy which highlighted their extreme lack of hospitality. Second, the food was served in paper plates, plastic spoons and forks and plastic water cups. I have been to several restaurants in Chicago and none did actually serve in paper plates. For a second we thought as if we are buying food from a food truck ! I mean come on guys we pay for you to serve us on paper plates and plastic spoons.Third and maybe the most important, the FOOD WAS HORRIBLE. We ordered Schezwan chicken and all we found was 3 tiny pieces of chicken and lots and lots of onions. It was basically Schezwan onions ! The dumplings were HORRIBLE too ! They had a thick shell and tiny portions of cabbage and chicken( though I doubt there was any chicken). There are several good restaurants in Chinatown which serve not only good food but also also serve in a good presentable manner with the required hospitality ! For Hing Kee management : Guys if you don’t want to serve, then don’t open the dine-in option, just have delivery. You guys are setting a bad example for Chinatown restaurants.

I went there at 5 pm on a Saturday. We didn't have to wait at all due to the efficiency of the staff who were also very attentive. We ordered the soup dumplings, scallion pancakes, and Mapo tofu. The soup dumplings were by far the best part of the meal and made the trip worth it. The scallion pancakes were just alright and the Mapo tofu left something to be desired. It was pretty bland compared to other Mapo tofu dishes I've head.  Definitely try the soup dumplings! Also, everything is very reasonably priced. My total was approximately $36.

Friend recommended to try their famous house made noodles and scrumptious dumplings. Finally the lockdown is over and indoor dining has started so we decide to try this place. We ordered: spicy dumplings in chilli oil, scallion pancakes ( oh my god its a must try), stir fry and schezwan style chicken with white rice. Dumplings and pancakes were really good. For the main course chicken was okayish so was the stir fry, i have had a lot better.  But sure for dumplings hing kee is a must visit.  Located in the heart of china town, nearby parking available, moderately priced, huge huge huge menu.

My teenage kids live for their Xiao Long Bao (pork soup dumplings) from this restaurant.  The best in Illinois. While I personally like them, they are not my personal favorite. My favorite of this restaurant is their salt and pepper spicy chicken wings. The best chicken wings ever!! I’m not a huge fan of chicken wings drowning in bbq sauce, and theirs is amazing. Spicy, a bit hot, not over cooked, crispy skin, tender meat, and delicious. And NO bbq sauce. And yet super flavorful. My kids are old enough to drive to Chinatown on their own, (we live in the far north suburbs of Chicago, and it’s an hour drive to get to this restaurant, but it is worth it. ). They don’t want mom to come along - they want to spread their wings and this Chinatown area is safe so I’m ok with it - but I always insist that they bring back the chicken wings to me. They went yesterday and I ate some last night. Didn’t disappoint, again for the Nth time. Truly they are delicious.
Good food, reasonable prices, okay service (not the most friendly employee, but not rude too). The outdoor dining has heating and windows for ventilation.

It was my first time here and it was great. I heard great things about their Xiao Long Bao (soup dumplings) and yes, it did not disappoint. We ordered the pork dumplings. The soup flavor and the dumplings themselves were yummy, flavorful, and perfectly cooked. The side (ginger soy) sauce was also unique and good with the dumplings, but I preferred no sauce. Staff makes them fresh and right in front, so you can see them create these pillows of goodness. Service was a bit slow, but they were very busy. However, staff was friendly and the restaurant seemed family ran. We didn't try anything else, but the dumplings, but the menu looked good! There's no WiFi here, there's a bathroom towards the back, and there's limited seating. When we left, there was a line out the door. I recommend their Xiao Long Bao, but everything else looked good, coming to other people's tables.

Great spot for xiao long bao or noodle soups. Their noodles are handmade and have this really nice chewiness and consistency throughout. Their spicy boiled beef noodles or beef brisket noodles soups would be my recommendation! Other noteworthy items here would be the salt and pepper egg tofu and the fish filet over noodles. Definitely one of my favorite spots in Chicago's Chinatown area.

If I had the option to rate this place below 1, I would do that. I have had 2 consecutive inadequate experiences.  First experience - we randomly chose to go here in the afternoon because it seemed busy and the lady making fresh dumplings you could see from the window seemed like a sure enough sign to go in and enjoy the food. We were asked to sit in their upstairs part of the restaurant so we did. There were about 5 tables upstairs and were in the process of settling in and ordering. Well, we waited to order with no acknowledgement. We made phone calls, replied to emails and chatted amongst each other. In the meantime, another tourist family came in and requested for a table of 4 and the staff blatantly refused service even though there were 6 empty tables. The family were visibly embarrassed and left saying that we should just go elsewhere. That was a sign for us that the service was not at all hospitable. After waiting for close to 20 minutes after being told that they will be coming to take our order, we left. No one cared. And we enjoyed a nice meal across the street.  Second experience - we got food delivered from this place just to give a second chance and try their food. Big big mistake. The food was undercooked, not tasty at all, reeked of fish-oyster sauce and smell. Nothing was labeled so we didn't know what dumpling was what. It literally felt like a bland, not appetizing blind testing. Probably only have 4 dumplings and egg drop soup from our entire order and everything was wasted, unfortunately. But those dumplings and soup were enough to give us a stomach ache and so much gas all night long. It was a horrible experience.  I didn't take any pictures of this place or the food because it was definitely not worth it.  This restaurant lacks in all aspects of a good dining experience. They need to update their cooking skills and service. Would not recommend this restaurant.

This place is absolutely legend! We keep coming back for more, to enjoy the authentic taste of noodles that is found in China! Their noodles carry tastes unique to China that is unlike the Malaysian, Taiwanese or Hong Kong cuisine.  Their noodles are hand made and have a Q factor that is firm and springy, really terrific and addictive noodles!  Today we tried the dan dan mian and spicy chicken noodles. Both Sichuan specialties with tons of aromatic spices.  Dan dan mian is fried minced pork with a healthy dose of sesame paste, Sichuan pepper and chili oil, making the broth rich and complex, and is bowl exploding with aromatic layers and flavors.  Laziji noodles is basically spicy chicken noodles. The broth is a clear chicken soup that is clean and sweet, and topped with marinated chicken infused with  Sichuan chilli peppers, spicy bean paste, and Sichuan peppers. This gives the basic broth a extra layer of flavor profile. However it's not as spicy as laziji normally is.

Soup dumpling: 4.5 star rest of the menu: 2.5 star  I have become a regular at Hing Kee since moving to Chicago six months ago. I first heard about Hing Kee from friends who mentioned their soup dumplings are some of Chicago's best. These hand-made xiaolongbao's did not disappoint. They are extremely soupy and the skins are just thin enough to hold the hefty amount of filing and soup. I would say I'm quite picky about the thickness of the skin and I think they definitely hit the marks here. What I like most about their xiaolongbao is actual the soup - packed with beef broth yet not too greasy. A bite of their xiaolongbao warms the soul!  However, besides the soup dumpling, I'm quite disappointed at the rest of their menu. I haven't had a solid dish to go with their amazing xiaolongbao. Their beef noodles were just average and many of the generic dish -- such as kunpao chicken -- are fairly below average for a Chinatown restaurant. I hope they can really improve their other dishes to really round out the experience.
